{
  "text": "Social cognition encompasses a wide range of abilities including interpretation of cues, social attribution, communication, interaction and social inferencing, all subserved by a set of complex interacting distributed neural systems (e.g. [CITATION_1] Amodio and Frith, 2006) . Probably the most significant stimulus for human social information processing is the face. Faces are important for identifying one's social partner, interpreting communicative intent and emotional response as well as for inferring more complex social attributions, stereotypes and appraisals. It is, therefore, not surprising that so many social cognitive studies have focused on face processing, including studies on ASD and WMS.",
